column168: A driver transporting a rolloff box containing hazardous material stopped for the night at a truckstop.  The next morning, while conducting his routine pretrip inspection, noticed material leaking from the rear door of the box.  He donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and placed absorbent material on the ground where the spill was leaking.  A response team was notified and cleaned up the spill and sealed the gasket where the spill was coming from.  The absorbent material was loaded into the box along with the spilled material.  The truck then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility where the load was delivered without further incident.  The state of Missouri (Cindy Thompson) was notified and assigned case number 1005050819CMT to the incident.
column169: At the time of pickup, no leaks had occurred.  During transportation, the gasket of the box leaked causing the spill.  The origin location was notified that the spill occurred and will instruct drivers to use better caution when picking up this material to insure gaskets are properly seated.

column168: The shipper loaded 24 drums on the carrier's trailer at the shipper's facility. The drums were not transferred to another trailer by the carrier during any phase of transportation from origin to the carrier's final destination terminal. A strong odor was noticed coming from the trailer U/A to the carrier's Indianapolis terminal. The trailer was closed and moved to an unoccupied area at the carrier's facility. An emergency response team was called to manage the spill and remove the waste. The drum was reported to have a small pin hole seemingly from a drum dolly or impacted by the drum loaded in front of the leaking drum. The contractor overpacked the leaking drum and the shipper will take the drum back for inspection. The clean up material was removed by the contractor. The spill was managed in 5 hours from the time it was recognized to the end of the clean up. No further actions are required at this time.

column168: A van trailer was loaded with a shipment of hazardous waste storage batteries.  The driver, while making a routine check of his load, noticed a small leak from his trailer.  He opened the trailer and found that one of the batteries had leaked from a cell onto the trailer floor.  He donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and used absorbent pads to contain the liquid.  A response crew was notified who came and overpacked the leaking battery and cleaned up the trailer and material that had leaked onto the ground.  This material was placed into the salvage container used for the battery.  The trailer then continued without further incident to the intended waste disposal facility.  The state of Kentucky was notified of the incident and issued report #20101490.
column169: When the batteries were accepted for transportation and also reloaded at the truck transfer facility, there was no sign of leakage.  It is believed that the method used to secure the batteries to the pallet was insufficient.  All parties involved with the pickup and loading of the batteries have been informed and instructed to insure that the shipments are adequately secured to prevent movement during transportation.

column168: The shipper tendered container, PAFA551941-9/WB2288295, to Horizon Lines on 5/7/10 in Tacoma for loading to the Horizon Anchorage, AZ784E for transit to Anchorage. Vessel sailed and arrived in Anchorage, AK on 5/11/10. During a random inspection it was discovered UN1133/Class 3 was undeclared in with this represented non-hazardous shipment.  Pertinent parties were notifed and corrective action was taken for shipment to continue in accordance to regulatory requirements.
column169: Shipper must monitor the entire loading process, to capture all hazardous commodities, so that documentation, paperwork and segregation is properly followed, prior to tendering shipment to trucker and ocean carrier.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was being unloaded from a box truck at the intermediate truck transfer facility onto a trailer with multiple shipments destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  At the time of pickup, the drum had been checked by the driver and there were no signs of leaks.  While moving the drum, a small amount of material leaked through a pinhole leak in the closure.  The driver donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and contained the released material to the top of the drum with abosrbent pads.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent material used to clean up the spill.  The trailer loading was completed and the shipment went to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver was instructed to use more caution when inspecting drums prior to pickup.  The drum closure was found to have a small hole that had been drilled next to it, causing the small pinhole leak.  The generator was notified of the incident.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for the purpose of transloading shipments into various trailers destined for their intended waste disposal facilities.  A small leak of a solid material was noticed on the trailer.  The employees involved donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the material into a suitable salvage container.  The trailer floor was cleaned up with an absorbent material and cleaned with a cleaning compound.  All of the cleanup materials were placed into the salvage container and it was loaded onto the trailer for the intended waste disposal location.  Illinois Emergency Management Agency was notified of the spill and issued report number H-2010-0508.

column168: The Linde vehicle was traveling west on US Rt.56 approximately 20 miles east of Johnstown, Pa.  An oncoming tractor trailer traveling east lost control, striking an automobile, crossing the centerline and struck the Linde tractor trailer head-on.  The force of the impact resulted in the Linde trailer becoming detached from the tractor.  The trailer went over a guard-rail and rolled over down an embankment coming to rest on its side approximately 60ft from the roadway.  The tractor remained upright and came to rest against the guard-rail.  The wrecge was cleared from the roadway in approximately 12 hours.  The trailer remained at the crash site, was attended by a security person overnight,and was recovered the following morning    Due to the impact, the full trycock valve was knocked open and vented product for approximately 24 hours until the trailer was able to be recovered.  Due to the properties of Carbon Dioxide, the remining liquid in the trailer eventually sublimed to dry ice and ceased venting.  The  valve was able to be closed as the trailer was removed from the side of the mountain.    Both truck drivers perished in the accident.
column169: The accident is still under investigation by the Pennsylvania State Police.  At this time, there is not indication of Linde having any responsibility for this accident.      There are no reccomendations to prevent a re-occurence at this time.

column168: A BNSF switch crew in the railyard reported product odor emanating from CPCX 105068 (DOT 105J500W tank car). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and immediately inspected CPCX 105068. Intact seal EVONIK 0119895 was removed from valve housing cover to inspect the valve securement status. No liquid product was observed, but a slight residue product odor was present. The responder reported finding one liquid valve slightly open with its closure (blind) flange and its four flange bolts/nuts not tool tight. The responder closed this liquid valve and properly tool tightened the flange bolts/nuts. Also, the vapor line's closure (blind) flange bolts/nuts were found less than tool tight and these were tool tightened. After securement completed, no further product odor was detectable. Valve housing cover was resealed with seal numbered BNSF 174063. Response was concluded by 1245 hrs. CDT, 5/09/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF mechanical carman reported TILX 195808 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking from the top fitting area with product running down its side shell. TILX 195808 was cordoned-off in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected TILX 195808. The responder reported that all shipper seals were intact. Further detailed inspection at the valve housing revealed that the liquid valve was slightly open with its closure plug not tool tight (2 1/2 turns loose). The responder closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug ending the product release. Response was concluded by 1455 hrs. MDT, 5/15/2010. Product spillage on the side shell of TILX 195808 evaporated. No ground impact was observed other than product droplets on the surface of a crosstie under TILX 195808 which also evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column17: PUERTO RICO AIR MANAGEMENT SERVICE, INC DHL EXPRESS
column168: ON 05/11/2010 AIRCRAFT N802AA AND WHILE BEING OFF-LOADED BY DHL PERSONNEL. A HAZMAT SPILL OCCURRED DHL PERSONNEL DID NOT INFORMED IMMEDIATELY THE PIC OR PRAMS AIR OF THE SPILL.  SUBSEQUENTLY THE AIRCRAFT WAS RELOCATED TO OUR RAMP FACILITIES BY THE PIC PRAMS AIR PERSONNEL LEFT THE OFFICES WITHOUT KNOWLEDGE OF SUCH OCCURRENCE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 23:50 LOCAL THE HAZMAT SPILL WAS REPORTED TO PRAMS AIR MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL, MORE THAN 2 HOURS AFTER THE OCCURRENCE.  INSTRUCTIONS WERE IMMEDIATELY TRANSMITTED TO SECURE THE AIRCRAFT.  AT DEPARTURE FROM SANTO DOMINGO THE PIC WAS NEVER INFORMED OR ISSUED A "PILOT NOTIFICATION FORM".  FURTHER CONVERSATION WITH LOCAL DHL MANAGERS/SUPERVISOR INFORMED THAT SANTO DOMINGO DHL, HANDLER DOES NOT HAVETHE REQUIRED AUTHORIZATION TO HANDLE HAZMAT.  DHL PERSONNEL INFORMED THE HAZMAT DANGEROUS GOODS HOTLINE AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR A CLEAN UP TEAM (CLEAN HARBOR ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE) TO  PERFORM AN AIRCRAFT CLEAN UP FIRST THING IN THE MORNING.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS CLEANED AND SERVICED FOLLOWED BY A REPORT ISSUED BY CLEAN HARBOR ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE.  THE DETAILED INFORMATION INCLUDED IN THIS REPORT IS THE DOT 5800.1 REPORT DHL SUBMITTED BY THE LOCAL DHL EXPRESS MANAGER, IN FACT THIS IS WHY WE KNOW ALL THE SPECIFICS ON THE HAZMAT SINCE NO DOCUMENTATION WAS PROVIDED TO PRAMS AIR BEFORE OR UPON ARRIVAL.

column168: 5/7/2010: At 12:28AM, CR crew FD46 was performing yard switching operations at CR's North Yard, Detroit, MI, facility, to make up cars for delivery to customer, PVS Chemical, Detroit, MI.  During movement of tank car GATX 60780, load, Hydrochloric Acid, crew members noted "smoking" originating from the top of the railcar.  Car was set out and isolated.      Emergency contractor Eagle SWS (Findlay, OH) performed an inspection later that morning in daylight hours, advising the OSECO 165# safety vent frangible disc had ruptured, as designed.  Further inspection by on-scene representatives of original customer PVS Chemical, noted the ruptured disc found by Eagle SWS personnel, was not in compliance with DOT Hazardous Materials Regulations, due to incompatibility.  The plastic film that is supposed to be affixed to the underside of the frangible disc to prevent product vapor/liquid from decomposing the disc while in use, was not present.  A new and compatible safety vent frangible disc, properly rated for the car, was used for replacement.      Car did not require extensive clean up due to heavy rains that were reported falling at the time of the incident, and proceding response.  Car was wiped down regardless, ph readings satisfied, and car forwarded onto original destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Our driver pulled over to the shoulder of the Interstate to avoid a rear end collision. In doing so pulled over into the grass area. He then tried to pull back onto the highway and caught the curb. The truck then rolled over on it's right side.   Action taken: The Lafayette Haz-Mat team was notified. The Rayne city police were called to the scene along with the Louisiana State Police Haz-Mat Division.  The leakage occured due to when the tank rolled over and landed on it's side the ball valve on the christmas tree hit a root in the ground causing it to open an leak product.   The valve was closed by the outside contract people that was called to assist.   The duration of the leak was approximately 5 hours with the valve half open and the product flowing through the dirt that was caked up in the crash box area.   A dirt dike was built to advoid the release to travel any further than it did. The spilled product was neutralized by the contract employees.
column169: I have no recommendations.

column168: On 5/14/10 at approximately 1520 hours a Dana Transportation tanker truck had just completed receiving a load of approximately 3500 gallons of caustic soda solution when it was discovered that the volume on the truck exceeded the maximum allowable weight for NJDOT.  While arrangements were being made for a truck to truck transfer an IMTT Operator discovered liquid dripping from the bottom of the trailer compartment.  The IMTT Operator immediately placed a 5-gallon pail under the trailer to contain the drips.  The cause of the leak appeared to be with the internal compartment.  The second truck was brought over to the leaking truck and the entire contents was transferred to the second truck.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components to prevent recurrences.

column168: Driver failed to negotiate right curve in two-lane roadway and crossed over other lane of traffic and into the mountain.  Vehicle rolled onto the drivers side as it went up the side of the mountain.  Rock and debris pierced the tank.  The unit then rolled back onto roadway resting on the passenger side.  The driver was taken via ambulance to nearest hospital.  114 barrels of crude oil spilled from the tank but did not penetrate beyond the surface of the road or nearby dirt.  All oil began to setup on the surface at the current temperature.  Cleanup efforts began immediately after the driver and truck were removed from the scene.  Worked with the Tri-County Health Dept. on remediation plans and approvals.  All cleanup was completed within a few days.  Final grading on the sides of the road took place within a week.
column169: We are currently awaiting the police report to determine what factors they believe led to the crash.  It appears that the driver was either distracted or was going to fast to negotiate the right hand curve in the road.  Flying J Transportation has monthly safety training for each driver.  We also have training programs in place that specifically address speeding and distracted driving, both of which the driver had been instructed on in the last 2 years.  Faulty equipment was not a factor in the accident, which was supported by the DOT inspection of the vehicles after the accident.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #28726/CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. FILE #2020020001:                                                                                                     ON MAY 5, 2010 AT APPROXIMATELY 1849 HOURS (CTZ), MR. TIRO BELTRAN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. BILL HERRON OF CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. (CTI).  MR. HERRON INFORMED MR. BELTRAN THAT IT HAD BEEN REPORTED THAT A POLYPROPYLENE BAG (CONTAINING 2,200 POUNDS OF SULFAMIC ACID) HAD FAILED AND RELEASED A PORTION OF SULFAMIC ACID.  THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED THE TRAILER FLOOR AND A SMALL AREA ON AN ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED MR. MIKE O'BRIEN (CTI DRIVER) FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION REGARDING THE RELEASE.  MR. O'BRIEN OPENED THE REAR TRAILER DOORS AT WHICH TIME A PORTION OF SULFAMIC ACID (POWDER) FELL OUT OF THE TRAILER.  MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (NRC) AND REQUESTED THAT NRC MOBILIZE PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT TO THE INCIDENT SITE.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL OPENNED THE TRAILER DOORS.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE BAG AND THE STRAPS WERE SECURED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE BAG HAD BEEN WRAPPED WITH SHRINK-WRAP AND STRAPS HAD BEEN PLACED AROUND THE BAG AND THE STRAPS WERE SECURED TO THE TRAILER WALLS.  IT WAS OBERVED THAT THE BAG HAD SHIFTED, BREAKING THE SHRINK-WRAP AND THE BAG PARTIALLY SLIPPED OFF THE PALLET.  THE WEIGHT OF THE PRODUCT CAUSED THE SEAM ON ONE SIDE OF THE BAG TO FAIL.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED THE REAR RIGHT CORNER OF THE TRAILER FLOOR, THE TRAILER BUMPER, AND A SMALL AREA ON THE ASPHALT.  THE IMPACTED AREA ON THE TRAILER FLOOR MEASURED APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET BY 6 FEET.  THE IMPACTED AREA ON THE ASPHALT MEASURED APPROXIMATELY 1 FOOT BY 2 FEET.  THE RESPONSE TEAM DONNED THE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN CLEANUP OPERATIONS.  ALL THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND PLACED IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER (BAG.)  APPROXIMATELY 200 POUNDS OF THE SULFAMIC ACID PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED.  A FORKLIFT WAS THEN UTILIZED TO LIFT THE DAMAGED BAG AND PLACE IT INTO A NEW BAG.  THE RESPONSE TEAM THEN UTILIZED A NEUTRALIZING  AGENT TO WIPE DOWN THE IMPACTED AREAS.  THE BAG WAS THEN PLACED BACK INTO THE TRAILER AND THE UNIT WAS RELEASED.
column169: Continued driver training.  Notify shipper of incident so that they may determine and implement a better and effective way of securing bags on pallets.

column168: We, Univar USA Inc., arrived at our customer's facility to deliver a bulk truck load of Sodium Hypochlorite. All hoses and air lines, set at 20 psi, were hooked up to begin the unloading process. As product began to flow, a customer's employee noticed a small leak coming from the semi-permanent air line attached to a PVC coupling below the line valve. As he made the driver aware of the leak, the driver investigated the leak at which time the air line ruptured from the PVC coupler spraying the driver in the face. Approximately 35 gallons of material escaped the vessel onto the concrete loading area floor before equipment could be shut down to stop the release of material. Immediate clean up procedures took place with absorbent boom socks and pillows utilized. This immediate action prevented any material from entering storm drain or waterways.
column169: This particular tank trailer will be sent directly to our repair shop to have all fittings inspected and replaced as necessary to avoid future incidents. All other tank trailers in our fleet will undergo similar inspections and repairs as necessary.

column168: On 5-5-2010 a 19 year old female tried passing several cars on a rural two lane highway and apparently did not see us coming the opposite direction. According to several wittnesses, she had room to pull back into her lane but for reasons unknown she did not. Our driver who was fully loaded moved over as far off the road as possible to avoid a collision, but the other driver made no attempt to move back over. The left front of our truck collided with the left front of the car and forced our truck to swerve hard left which caused the trailer to roll over and catch on fire. The truck went out into a field and was completely consumed by fire along with the fuel it was carring. The other driver died of her injuries from the collision.
column169: Our driver was doing everything safe he could. He was traveling under the speed limit, he had has lights on (8:30am) and tried to move over without going into a ditch on the side of the road.

column168: Tommy Madison and James Finan were assigned to unload this trailer.  Upon openening the door, they detected an odor and saw that the trailer floor was wet.  They immediately contacted their supervisor.  Upon inspection, it was determined that the cap on the valve at the bottom of this tote was not t  ightened.  Therefore about 1 cup worth of liquid had spilled out.  The area was cleaned up and the cap was tightened.  The shipment was placed in the haz-mat section of the dock for further inspection by our OSandD department.  The tote does not appear to be leaking anymore.
column169: The shipper needs to be made aware of this incident so that they properly secure these totes.

column168: At 17:00 on May 3, 2010, an NOPB switching crew smelled an odor coming from tank car UTLX 46518 in Cotton Warehouse Yard in New Orleans.  The crew notified the yardmaster on duty, Michael Majoue, and the switching yard was shut down.  Majoue notified the LA State Police, the New Orleans Fire Department, Port of New Orleans Harbor Police, the LA Department of Environmental Quality (DEQ), and NOPB Assistant Bridge Supervisor Eric Stoulig.  Stoulig notified United States Environmental Services and requested that they come out to investigate.  The Louisiana DEQ, the New Orleans Fire Department, United States Environmental Services (USES), and several NOPB officials all responded to the incident.    The New Orleans Fire Department arrived on site at approximately 17:15 and determined that tank car UTLX 46518 was an empty residue car last containing a Class 3 Flammable Liquid NOS (Crude Sulfate Turpentine, Alpha-Pinene).  Although the car was venting residue gas, Fire Department personnel agreed that the car posed no immediate threat to the public and departed at 18:30.    USES personnel arrived on site at approximately 18:00.  Upon inspection of tank car UTLX 46518, USES determined that there was a faulty 2.5” vacuum relief valve on the tank car, causing the empty residue car to vent gases.  Kelsey Tamplain of USES made arrangements with the car’s owner to have Rescar replace the faulty valve the next day, May 4, 2010.    On May 4, 2010, John McCrossen of NOPB met with Kelsey Tamplain of USES and Theresa LoGuidice of the DEQ at 09:30 at the NOPB Cotton Warehouse Yard office.  While waiting for Rescar to arrive with the replacement valve for the tank car, USES personnel scrubbed the vapors with the use of a carbon drum.  Rescar arrived at 13:15 and changed the valve, fixing the leak, and making the car safe to move.  The car was secured and released back to the railroad for transport at approximately 13:50.  The LA State Police were called to close out the incident at approximately 13:50.
column169: Car owners should more carefully perform periodic inspections and maintenance on tank car components.

column168: On 05/05/10 at 09:26 hrs., personnel in the CSXT yard in Brewton, AL discovered GATX 61463, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking vapor from the top of the car. According to the information obtained, the following occurred.   While stopped in a parking lot off Hamilton Mill Parkway, driver detected a release from the pressure relief valve in the crash box on top of the tanker.  Apparently, there was a faulty O ring on the valve, which caused the release.  Approximately 1/2 cup of free product had released and evaporated upon contact with the air.  The Slay Transportation Co., Inc. driver remained on site, awaiting maintenance personnel who responded to repair the valve.  Valve was repaired with no further incident, and shipment went on to its destination.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty valve, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to perform routine maintenance, and train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 05/20/10 at 01:11 hours, personnel in the CSXT Niagara yard in Niagara Falls, NY reported tank car GATX 57432, a load of Hydrochloric Acid was leaking vapor from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Occidental Chemical Corp. was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-05-20-00007).  The shipper dispatched two personnel to the yard to investigate and found that the Salco housing was intact and that the Zook rupture disc had blown. Occidental Chemical representatives replaced the Zook rupture disc and the leak stopped. No product residue was found on top of the tank car.     An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not required for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code:  441   NARRI:  2 (5+3+0) X (2+0) = 32

column168: Driver first arrived at the customer site and proceeded to start unloading.  A leak developed immediately.  They stopped unloading and emptied out the cavity between the internal and external valve.  The trailer was brought back to our terminal in Gary, In where the product was transferred into another trailer.  Upon inspection a crack in the housing of the valve itself was identified.  The trailer has been in service for less than 1 year.  No visible signs that it was hit or accident damaged and later inspection didn't reveal any pitting or corrosion to the valve.  Labelling it as a faulty valve.
column169: The crack is not readily visible and is not something I would expect the driver to have seen on pre-trip inspection.  We will be bringing this to the manufacturer for inspection and reimbursement of a new valve as this should not have happened.

column168: Tank car UTLX 11074 was found to be releasing vapor from a flange in the Alton Southern Railyard on 05/03/10.  Hulcher Services was dispatched and found 3 bolts missing on the flange.  Hulcher applied the bolts and sercured the car properly stopping hte vapor release.  No injuries or exposures recorded with this incident and no waterways were affected.

column168: A driver picked up a shipment of hazardous waste and returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility where the shipment would be offloaded and consolidated with other shipments destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  While unloading the trailer, the dock personnel noticed that a drum had leaked onto the trailer floor approximately 1/2 gallon of liquid.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the spilled material was cleaned up with an absorbent material and the drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container.  The trailer floor was cleaned up with a cleaning compound and returned to service.  The overpacked drum was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  Louisiana State Police were called and assigned incident number 10-02757 to the case.
column169: The driver did not notice any signs of leakage or corrosion at time of pickup.  The generator was notified of the event and cautioned about the use of old used drums.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: A driver transporting a rolloff container containing hazardous waste was trying to unload the box into containment at the ten day storage yard.  The container became stuck on the bed of the truck while trying to offload it.  The driver (owner operator) tried to raise the box further to get it to slide off of the rails.  This movement caused approximately 25 gallons of the material to spill onto the ground.  A response crew was notified, they arrived, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the material, reloading back into the rolloff container.  The container and truck chassis were also cleaned up with a suitable cleaning compound.  Illinois IEPA was notified and they assigned incident number H-2010-0561 to the case.
column169: The driver was given a verbal warning and advised to seek help if he cannot unload a container properly without tipping the box at such an angle to cause a spill.  The driver will be retrained on proper loading and unloading of rolloff containers.

column168: Driver was entering a construction zone where 2 lanes narrowed in to one. The right front steer tire of the tractor dropped off the right shoulder of the highway causing the driver to lose contol of the truck. The truck rolled over in the median of the interstate. As a result of the rollover, the stem seal of an internal valve started leaking anhydrous ammonia vapors. The leak was small and was fixed by tightening the stem packing nut.
column169: Talked to driver about the importance of paying closer attention when driving through construction zones, especially at night.

column168: Hollywood Yard MYO reported a release of spent Sulfuric acid from tank car GATX 6558 that injured a Union Pacific conductor and was transported via ambulance to the hospital. After inspection of tank car GATX 6558 the quick fill port was not secured; swing bolts were less than tool tight which caused the release during switching opperations. The quick fill port was secured and the car was cleaned and released to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A driver transported a rolloff container containing hazardous waste to the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility.  He stated that there were no leaks in transit.  During a routine check of the container, a leak was noticed coming from the rear door.  The gasket sealing the rear door of the container was leaking and a small amount had spilled onto the ground in containment.  A response crew was summoned, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spill with an absorbent material, then placed it into the rolloff box.  The box was taken into to the intended waste disposal facility where it was unloaded without further incident.
column169: The gasket failed on the rolloff box causing the small leak.  The driver was cautioned to check all gaskets and seals carefully when picking up rolloff containers.  The maintenance department has been instructed to carefully check gaskets and rear seals when repairing and inspecting rolloff containers.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Reeves Brothers tractor trailer was carrying lead acid batteries.  The tractor trailer was involved in an accident which resulted in the spillage of the lead acid from the batteries.  This incident is considered a one time incident.  Once the incident occurred Reeves Brothers retained Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) to oversee environmental remediation.  ERTS contacted SEMO Environmental, whcih had also been contacted by the Missouri Dept. of Natural Resources, to perform remediation activities.  SEMO personnel arrived on site and began containerizing the batteries involved in the accident.  SEMO personnel utilized soda ash to neutralize the released materials.  All released materials were containerized for transportation to the recycling and disposal facilities.
column169: This incident is considered a one time incident.

Spent Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Motor RSRM-109 C/F was observed to have propellant colored residue in the case after recovery from the ocean following a space shuttle launch. The areas were power washed using the standard procedure to remove unburned propellant. These procedures failed to remove the colored material. The engineers determined that the colored resdue was iron oxide.    After the rocket motor case arrived at our facility in Clearfield, Utah for refurbisment the operators who clean the case for reuse had concerns about the colored residue and as a precaution samples were sent to our laboratory for evaluation. Laboratory tests determined the residue was unburned solid propellant (TP-H1148, EX1982080002).    ATK technicians mechanically removed approximately 2 to 3 pounds of propellant and rubber liner which was transported to our Promontory, Utah facility for disposal. This rocket motor contains 273,164 pounds of propellant before it is launched.
column169: Our corrective action to this incident is that should a questionable patch of material be found after lanunch and cannot be removed using our standard procedures Design Engineering will assess if propellant is present, additional pressure washing will be applied. If the material is not removed by pressure washing it will be removed by manual excision prior to shipping the post fire rocket motor cases back to Utah.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A 55 GALLON DRUM OF LIQUID WAD DAMAGED DUE TO FALLING OFF THE BARREL ATTACHMENT.  THE DRUM AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: PROPER UNLOADING AND LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME HANDLING DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS ANHAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. APPROPRIATE DRUM ATTACHMENTS MUST BE SAFELY USED TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGING. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. REMOVE AND AVOID OBSTRUCTIONS IN LANE OF TRAVEL TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND UNSAFE SITUATIONS. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICAL .RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: AN OUTBOUND EMPLOYEE ON THE GREEN WALL NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE ON AN IRREG TRAIN & NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR, ABEL.  ABEL NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS BY RADIO.  WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I NOTICED THAT IT WAS A CORROSIVE SO I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS AS DIRECTED BY MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEET.  I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE TO A LINED SPILL TUB.  I TOOK THE PH OF THE LIQUID ON THE IRREG TRAIN.  I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID WITHIN THE 6-9 RANGE & THEN SOLIDIFIED IT WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT.  I SWEPT UP THE SODIUM BICARB/ABSORBANT USED IN CLEANUP AND ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TUB. I DOUBLE-CHECKED TO ENSURE ALL RESIDUE WAS REMOVED FROM THE IRREG TRAIN.  THEN I TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 OF THE 4 CAPS HAD COME LOOSE.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering unleaded gas to a customer location. While unloading the driver noticed product leaking out of the vapor recovery system. The driver immediately shut off the flow of product but approximately 10 gallons leaked into the concrete. Spill rags were used to clean up the spill. The fuel did not reach soil or drains. The local fire department did respond but no work was required. The spill rags were taken back to the terminal for proper disposal. The driver had mistakenly calculated 90% safe fill of 5900 gallons not taking the 9500 gallon tank less the 5900 gallons in there and then taking 90% of the difference.
column169: The driver was immediately suspended for one day and retrained on proper unloading procedures. The driver did not take time to thoroughly read the veeder root reading and recheck his calculations. An incident prevention observation will be conducted prior to releasing driver back to work.

column168: THIS WAS A LOAD OF ACUITY SPECIALTY PRODUCTS THAT HAS ORDERS MIXED ON THE PALLETS AND IS A SORT AND SEGREGATE TRAILER.  THE PALLETS WERE DOUBLE-STACKED, WITHOUT DUNNAGE BETWEEN THEM IN SOME CASES.  THE PALLET THAT SUFFERED DAMAGE DID NOT PROVIDE A LEVEL STACKING SURFACE AND 3 CARTONS ON  THE BOTTOM OF THE SKID COLLAPSED AS A RESULT OF THE WEIGHT OF THE PALLETS STACKED ON TOP OF IT BY THE SHIPPER CAUSING ITS CONTENT TO BE LOST.  THE CARTONS WERE 1.  INDUSTRIAL PURPLE DEGREASER CVM UN3266 AND A SECOND CARTON OF NON-HAZ MOLD AND MILDEW STAIN REMOVER, THE THIRD CARTON OF NON-HAZ PINE MULTI-PURPOSE CLEANER.  ALL THREE WERE PLACED IN SALVAGE RECOVERY DRUMS AND HELD IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BAY PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: USE A DECK TRAILER OR PALLET RACKS.  DON'T STACK UNEVEN SKIDS OF HAZMAT ON ONE ANOTHER.

column168: PALLET OF PAINT STACKED UP.  LOAD SHIFTED, 2 FIVE-GAL PAILS TIPPED, ONLY MINOR SPILLAGE.  THE PAILS AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: JUST NEEDS TO DO A BETTER JOB OF SECURING FRT.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM; LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: On May 26, 2010 at 1840 hours, crew BR1 hitched up to cars on the Bradford Passing Siding.  The conductor then proceeded to walk back and make a cut behind the Crude Oil cars in order to spot these cars at the American Refining Crude Rack Track.  Upon arriving at car GATX 300576, the conductor noticed that this car was leaking from the top dome.  He stated that the leak was occurring in drips from multiple locations around the dome.  Given the conductors perceived magnitude of the leak, he called 911, notified the northbound approaching train to stop safely short of the area and then reported the incident to the dispatcher.  The dispatcher then notified CHEMTREC as well as all necessary BPRR management.  This car was loaded with Petroleum Crude Oil.  Local fire responded and contained the spill with buckets and pads until responders from American Refining were present.  American Refining responded with a pump truck and pumped off enough product to relieve pressure in the tank and stop the leak.  The car was then spotted at the Crude Rack for unloading.  The car was later inspected by local FRA agent Timothy Rowan at which time he concluded that the car leaked as a result of being over filled and that a "slight Manway Gasket tear was detected in the area of the hinge possibly as a result of over tightening of the Swingbolts".

column168: May 25, 2010: At approximately 2025 hours, Conrail crew reported seeing a small stream of product slowly cascading down the one side of tank car NATX 280048 (non-insulated), load Xylene, while car was located on the Speedway Track, Port Richmond Yard (serving yard for customer, Kinder Morgan), Philadelphia, PA.    Conrail emergency response contractor REACT Environmental Services, Inc., was called to respond to effect securement and any remediation.  Inspection by REACT noted the leak originating from underneath the protective housing.  Seal #025817 was removed and housing cover opened.  Leak originating from the threaded 3" liquid valve where it was threaded into the valve's 4-bolt mounting plate.  Attempts to tighten the threaded valve with varying size pipe wrenches proved unsucessful.  Evidence of thread damage due deterioration and old teflon-like tape and/or pipe thread dope was noted.    Internal pressure reduced through air valve, and leak ceased.  Very high ambiant temperatures (in 90's) reported that day.  Further attempts made to tighten or remove valve to repair after car was vented down to "0", again, proved unsuccessful.  Reported any product that had been released had evaporated prior to contacting ground.  Magnetic float closed system gauging device read 10-1/2" outage.  Car secured for evening.  Sunoco, Philadelphia, PA corporate inquired to FRA if movement approval would be required to move the car from its current location (yard located next to neighborhood), and FRA replied no movement approval required, citing Section 174.50 of Title 49, CFR.    May 26, 2010.  Customer notified of car's condition and gave approval to have car moved into the plant at first opportunity so it could be placed at the unloading rack.  REACT representatives re-inspected car and noted similar small release the following day, due to ambiant temperature and internal pressure increase.  Car vented down again; new protective housing seal "REACT 002323" applied to protective housing, and car was moved by Conrail crew to original destination (an approximate 1-mile move).  REACT escorted car while in transit, and no further leakage/exceptions noted.  Car placed at customer unloading rack at approximately 2PM.    Sunoco, Inc., Philadelphia, PA, applied for, and obtained, FRA Movement Approval "FRA-10050318" for car to be moved, after unloading, to GE Railcar Repair, Sayre, PA.

column168: May 26, 2010: tank car NATX 50286, load, containing Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, NOS (Ammonium Chloride), arrived in CR Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, on track #18 Support, CR WPCA11-26.    May 27, 2010: At approximately 315am, CR Trainmaster D. Robertson reported car leaking in heavy streams at A-end of car, near the bottom, on the left side and down onto the body bolster.  CR emergency contractor REACT Environmental Services, Inc. contacted to respond, in addition to CR's Risk Management Department (N. Ferrone, Cheif Risk Officer, and A. Richter, Risk Manager-Hazardous Materials).    Upon arrival and inspection, heavy, multiple streams of product confirmed originating from behind the tank car's jacket, at the A-end corner, just outboard from the side and truck bolster.  Later estimate by REACT during vaccuming process during transfer determined leak rate at approximately 40 gallons an hour.  Troughs placed under A-end truck to contain product release.  Camden City Fire Department, Camden County Hazmat and Camden County Environmental Health and Hazmat also on scene at onset of incident, but deeming low hazard of product, nil contaminent to ground area due review of shipper MSDS (product used as ground fertilizer in current state as shipped) and control of incident, all responding agencies made decision to depart scene.    Entire contents transferred into 4 compatible vacuum cargo trucks. During transfer of 2nd load from car, there was a significant decrease in the streams of releasing product.  After transfer was complete (loaded cargo tanks returned product to original shipper, DuPont, Deepwater, NJ).  No further leakage from car.  Car was moved to #1 Heavy track in Pavonia Car Shop area.  Effected area on 18-Support was scraped and cleaned.  Based on information obtained from shipper, the heavy rains occurring in the area would neutralize any remaining product not captured (ph of product in raw state is 6.8-7.5).  Concentration displayed on MSDS supplied by shipper noted: Water: 69-85%; Ammonium Chloride: 15-31%; and, Isopropyl Alcohol: 0-0.3%).      May 28, 2010: REACT cleaned and purged/powerwashed inside of tank car.  Internal inspection conducted and noted multiple areas of shell pitting, corrosion and the suspected area of leakage noted cracking.  Shipper DuPont, obtained movement approval from FRA, via FRA-10050322, to have the car moved from CR's Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, to Alpha Technologies, Bayport, TX, for further cleaning, then onto Safety Railway in Aloe, TX for inspection and repair.

column168: Univar Material Handler was moving the container and noticed a wet spot on the concrete where it was being stored.  A Supervisor was notified and upon further investigation the outside container, a cubic yard box, was confirmed to be leaking.  A contract environmental cleanup company was called to repackage the contents into a new outside container.  A five gallon steel tight head pail was discovered to be leaking within the cubic yard box container.  The leaking package was identified, sealed, double bagged and placed into an overpack.  All other containers were also placed into a new overpack.  The inner packaging, a black plastic bag/liner, had no obvious defects or punctures but was observed to be leaking from a corner seam.  All contaminated solids were repacked in accordance with regulatory compliance.
column169: One recommendation would be to use two liners for the inner packaging.

column17: PAN AM RAILWAYS /SPRINGFIELD TERMINAL RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: Pan Am Railways Conductor was switching out track 3W in our East Deerfield yard and found car # PLMX 26350 Diethylenetriam, UN 2079, Class 8, PG II, wet around the top of the car from the tank car sloshing when moving back and forth in the yard.  Once the Conductor noticed this he stopped the move and notified the Train Master who informed him to place the car in a nearby in a safe location to be looked at by the Mechanical Department.  The Customer was also notified and RESCAR was called in to repair the car which was found to have a broken gasket in the Safety Valve Flange (PRO).  It was also noted by RESCAR that one of the bolts on the Safety Valve Flange was not very tight, this was also corrected after replacing the gasket.  The Estimate and the duration of the release was minor/vapor on the top of the car.
column169: In my opinion the Safety Valve Flange bolt was not tight enough, thus creating it to loosen up in transit and eventually causing the rupture to the gasket.  Careful check and documentation by the shipper of all bolts may be a way to lessen the incident.

column168: On arrival of trailer into UBY we noticed a light odor.  We stopped the trailer from coming to the dock, so I could look at the paper work and make sure it was safe.  We then put the trailer out on the pad and opened the doors to air out.  After an hour we then put the trailer to the dock.  We then went in to find out what happened.  We found that they had used dunnage all the way around the pails, but they did not brace or block it causing the pails to slide half off the skid and to rub against one another until one of the handle mounts rubbed a hole in the side of one of the pails allowing about 3 gallons to leak out onto the floor of the trailer.  We picked up the leaking pail and secured it in to a salvage drum so that no more leakage would happen.  Then we finished the clean up of the floor.
column169: I found that we need to make sure that we are blocking and bracing all hazardous shipments.  That way we will not have the shifting of the freight that led up to this event.  We should make sure that all shipments are secured in some from this would prevent the recurrence of this event again.

column168: On 5/21/10, a loader proceeded to load Ashland trailer #15910 with mineral spirits (Rule 66). The loader overloaded compartment #2, which has a capacity of 1,000 gallons. The loader then turned off the pump and closed the railcar. Approximately 60 gallons was captured in two catch pans with an additional 30 gallons impacting the asphalt. Absorbent and sand was used to dam and dike. The remaining product was placed in a drum for disposal.
column169: Awareness Items - 1. Outage alarm probe was in the appropriate trailer compartment but was not turned on. 2. Spill pans were placed under the overflow tubes in the back of the trailer; the overflow tubes in the front were missed and had no spill pans underneath them.    Root Causes - 1. The loader neglected to turn the outage alarm probe on before inserting it into the false dome lid on the trailer. 2. The loader was not situated at the top of the platform to closely monitor the meter.    Corrective Actions - 1. Verifier will ensure that the loader turns on the probe prior to it being placed in the dome. 2. Reinforce to all loaders the need to stay on top of the platform to monitor the meter while performing this transfer.

column168: Employee was traveling west bound on Regentview Ave. driving approximately 20-25 MPH.  Employee was in Third gear as he approached the intersection with Steward and Gray Road.  Employee depressed the clutch pedal and applied foot pressure to the brake pedal and did not get a response.  The truck continued forward as employee was approaching the Stop sign.  Employee witnessed a car traveling NB ion Stewart and Gray Rd. and was afraid that he was going to collide with it.  To avoid a collision with this vehicle he tried to turn his truck into the NB lane.  This turn caused Employee to lose control of the truck and it rolled over onto its left side.  Some liquid lines were damaged in the incident.  The Fire Department evacuated the area and did not allow Ferrellgas to approach the vehicle until approximately nine hours had passed.  When Ferrellgas was allowed to approach the vehicle Ferrellgas transferred the propane from the damaged vehicle to another vehicle.  The damaged vehicle was then up righted and towed.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: On 5/27/10, at 10:02 hours, personnel in the CSXT Yeoman yard in Tampa, FL discovered UTLX 206020, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Hawkeye Gold LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-05-27-00089).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the car had a broken pressure relief device valve and temporarily secured the leak.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Janet Fenton (641-648-8917).  The shipper contacted emergency response contractor, Rescar, to replace the pressure relief device.  The shipper is in the process of applying for a FRA Movement Approval to forward the tank car to destination.  This incident did require a special switching move.    Note:  A QA-7.1 Nonconformance Report is required for this incident.    Cause Code: 417  NARRI: 2 (5+3+0) + (2+0) = 32

column168: On 05/26/10 at 13:13 hours, FRA Inspector David Snyder was inspecting tank cars at the CSXT Sumter yard in Sumter, SC and discovered GATX 7219, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car had a blown 165lb. frangible disc. The car was decontaminated and released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 2 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While in the UPRR Bittle Yard located at 3100 Springer Road in Little Rock, Arkansas a leak was discovered coming from rail car GATX61397.  The Little Rock Fire Department responded to assess the site.  United States Environmental Services, LLC (USES)of Little Rock, Arkansas was dispatched to perform the cleanup and product transfer.      USES arrived on-site and met with a representative of the Little Rock Fire Department.  USES was informed that the rail car was leaking from a weep hole were the hand rails are welded to an end of the rail car.  The USES crew patched the rail car and the UPRR switch crew moved the rail car from the main line to the staging track for product transfer.  USES neutralized the spill area and rail car.  USES crew monitored the rail car for leaks overnight, until product transfer occurred the following day.    On Sunday, May 23, 2010 USES completed product transfer from the tanker.  USES will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.

column168: AS THE SHIFT WAS ENDING AT THE ROANOKE HUB, EMPLOYEES NOTICED A FULLY MARKED AND LABELED PACKAGE OF NITRIC ACID NEAR AN OUTBOUND DOOR.  THE PACKAGE WAS EMITTING SMOKE, SO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED.  AFTER THE FIRE FIGHTERS ARRIVED, THEY WITNESSED THE PACKAGE ERUPTING INTO FLAMES.  THEY EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE WITHOUT ANY INJURIES TO ANY PEOPLE OR DAMAGE TO THE BUILDING.  BY THE TIME THE FIRE WAS EXTINHGUISHED, THREE OF THE FOUR BOTTLES HAD CRACKED OPEN, ALTHOUGH IT IS SUSPECTED THE FIRE MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE BOTTLE DAMAGE.
column169: THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE FIRE IS HARD TO DETERMINE AFTER THE FACT.  FROM EVIDENCE AVAILABLE AFTER THE INCIDENT THE EXTERIOR OF THE PACKAGE DID NOT SHIW VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. HOWEVER, SUSPICIONS ARE THAT THERE MAY HAVE BEEN AN INTERNAL LEAK WITHIN THE PACKAGE, SUCH AS FROM A CAP, ALLOWING NITRIC ACID TO COME INTO CONTACT WITH THE FIBERBOARD PACKAGING.  SUCH LEAKS WOULD BE MINIMIZED THROUGH USE OF AN INTERMEDIATE PACKAGING LAYER (SEE 49 CFR 173.158).  HOWEVER, THERE IS NO EVIDENCE OF INTERMEDIATE PACKAGING IN THE DEBRIS REMAINING AFTER THE FIRE.

column168: On 05/21/10 at 01:58 hours, personnel in the CSXT Florence yard in Florence, SC discovered GATX 7458, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Savage FlexiFlo, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-05-21-00015).  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the air line plug was not applied, allowing product to escape during transportation.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Wendell Davis at 215-334-3149.  HEPACO personnel installed the air line plug and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and released for transport.  This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 132  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100
column169: Ensure tank cars are properly secured prior to issuing waybills and releasing for transportation.

column168: On 05/20/10 at 10:13 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Barr yard in Riverdale, IL discovered   UTLX 206020, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. leaking from the top of the car at the manway nozzle. The car was isolated and the shipper, Hawkeye Gold LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-05-20-00077).  Jim Briski, a CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager, was dispatched to the scene and found one manway cover securement bolt was less than tool tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Cory Bisgard (515-663-6437).  Jim Briski tightened the manway cover securement bolt and the leak stopped.  Jim Briski also inspected the liquid and vapor valves for securement and released the car for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 200   NARRI : 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: On 05/25/10 at 16:51 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon yard in Avon, IN discovered UTLX 640092, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Clariant Corp., IDEM, and the USEPA were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-05-25-00279). Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve bell cap was less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Jimmie Hartsell (704-960-2066). Summit personnel tightened the bottom outlet valve bell cap 1/2 turn and the leak stopped.  The car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  148  NARRI:  5 (3+1+0) x (2+0) = 40

column168: GATX 53875 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking liquid from the top fitting area of this tank car in the railyard. GATX 53875 was cordoned off awaiting inspection from BNSF contract responders. Air monitoring at GATX 53875's location was conducted by the contract responders and no airborne contaminants were detected. The contract responder reported the liquid stain traced back to the pressure relief device (PRD) atop GATX 53875. Spillage on the side shell was evaporating and no ground impact was noted. Assessment by the responder after all valves and fittings were inspected concluded that GATX 53875 was possibly overfilled. On 5/29/2010, GATX 53875 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for the contract responder to off-load a portion of the contents within GATX 53875 into a vac-truck. Approximately 1000 gallons was removed and placed into the vac-truck without incident. Afterwards, observed outage levels via the manway of GATX 53875 was acceptable at 13 inches. Commodity stain residue at the PRD and on the tank shell was wiped. The commodity in the vac-truck was delivered to the consignee for unloading. Intact seals at the manway closure, valve housing cover and the bottom outlet valve were replaced by seals numbered 000708, 000709 and 000799. No further spillage from GATX 53875 was reported during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the appropriate tank car loading outages; and the total securement and the mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: UTLX 204418 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the manway area during normal switching in the railyard. Movement was stopped and no further product release was observed when this tank car stood motionless. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected UTLX 204418. The responders reported that the shipper seal atop the manway lid was intact and all manway securement bolts were tool tight. Product spillage on the tank's side shell was evaporating and no ground spillage was observed. Further inspection into the manway securement revealed that the manway gasket was missing which prevented a good closure seal. A BNSF contract responder installed a new nitrile rubber manway gasket and resecured the manway closure. Valve securement was also checked and no exceptions were noted. Intact seal removed at the manway was CSE 506454 and replaced by TIS 5929 seal. Intact seal removed at the valve housing cover was CSE 506453 and replaced by TIS 5931 seal. Response was concluded by 2245 hrs. MDT, 5/30/2010. No further product release was noted from UTLX 204418 during subsequent rail movements.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: ON SUNDAY, MAY 9, WE WERE TRANSLOADING SULFURIC ACID FROM RAIL CARS TO TRUCKS.  WE HAVE TWO TRANSLOADING SITES WITH FULL CONTAINMENT AND AUTOMATED TRANSLOADING TOWERS AT EACH LOCATION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 16:00 HOURS THE ELECTRICAL POWER FAILED ON OUR NUMBER ONE SITE.  THE RAIL CAR IS UNLOADED USING AIR PRESSURE AND THE UNLOADING PROCESS CONTINUED WITHOUT THE FLOW CONTROLLER BEING ABLE TO SHUT OFF FLOW, THE ELECTRIC VALVE STAYED IN THE OPEN POSITION WITH LOSS OF POWER.  THE TRUCK BEING LOADED ON THE CONTAINMENT STARTED TO OVERFLOW ACID.  THE OPERATOR WAS SIGNALED BY A TRUCK DRIVER AND RAN TO THE EMERGENCY STOP BUTTON.  WITH NO POWER, THE EMERGENCY STOP DIDN'T WORK.  THE OPERATOR THEN WENT TO MANUAL SHUT OFF VALVES ON TOP OR RAIL CAR.  BY THE TIME THE EMPLOYEE REACHED THE MANUAL SHUT OFF VALVES ON TOP OF THE RAIL CAR A QUANTITY OF SULFURIC ACID HAD OVERFILLED THE TRUCK TRAILER AND SPILLED ONTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  ONCE THE FLOW WAS STOPPED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE HOSED OFF WITH WASH WATER WHICH ALSO DILUTED THE SULFURIC ACID.  THE SULFURIC ACID WAS THEN NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  THE QUANTITY OF ACID SPILLED WAS 148 GALLONS AS CALCULATED BY THE NUMBER OF 50 POUND BAGS OF SODA ASH ADDED TO BRING THE ORIGINAL ACID SOLUTION TO PH 7.0.  THE NEUTRALIZED SOLUTION WAS THEN PUMPED INTO A SECONDARY HOLDING TANK FOR FINAL REMOVAL.  NO EQUIPMENT WAS DAMAGED AND NO ONE WAS HURT BY THE INCIDENT.
column169: ADDITIONAL AWARENESS TRAINING FOR TRANSLOADING OPERATORS, IN PARTICULAR BEING MORE AWARE OF STATUS OF AUTOMATIC CONTROLS.  WE ARE INVESTIGATING THE CHANGE OF THE AUTOMATIC FLOW CONTROL VALVES THAT WILL FAIL SHUT OR CLOSED WITH LOSS OF ELECTRICAL POWER.  THE CURRENT VALVES REMAIN IN THE POSITION THEY WERE AT, OPEN OR CLOSED, WITH LOSS OF ELECTRICAL POWER.

column168: On 05/10/10 at 8:52 hrs., it was reported that tank car LTCX1809, MR 204W, load of Argon, Refrigerated Liquid, was leaking in train Q36409. CSXTransportation stopped the train at MP Ql 30 (Great Lakes Division, Greenwich Subdivision). Car was reported as: "putting out a cloud". CSXTdispatched emergency response contractor, SWS/Eagle, to respond to the scene. At 10:16 hrs., CHEMTREC (Report number 2010-05-10-00051)was notified. At 10:53 hrs., the Ohio EPA was notified, report number 1005-47-1236. At 13:12 hrs., SWS/Eagle responders reported the cabinet forLTCX1809 was sealed (KCS 968136) and they broke same to access fittings. SWS/Eagle personnel found the sample line valve open, the liquid linevalve open with its caps not tool tight and the packing gland for this valve to be less than tool tight. column168: THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED DUE TO RESIDUE ON OUTER PACKAGE. UPON INSPECTION OF INNER CONTENTS A FIRE EXTINGUISHER HAD DISCHARGED INSIDE OF THE BOX.  THE KEY WAS FOUND DISLODGED IN THE BOTTOM OF BOX.

Driver hooked up trucks pump on the off-side of truck to the above ground tank, came around and checked pump on the driver side of truck to make sure cap was secure.  Driver turned on the PTO and pumped approximately 1,000 gallons of product off the tanker and felt comfortable with the operation and entered the truck to bump up the pumpspeed.  Driver noticed that the motor on the truck relaxed.  Driver looked around and saw that product was coming out of the pump on the driver side.  He immediately shut down the PTO, shut down the truck, could not get to the emergency shut-off valve for the product coming out of the pump so he ran around the truck and shut down the valve handles to stop the flow of product.  The cap on the driver side of the pump had vibrated loose and pressure caused it to blow off.  The driver had secured it with a double-eye hook.  One side of the hook had a quarter inch opening in it and the dog ear ring worked through the opening and allowed the cap to open up and blow off.  When product flow stopped personnel working on site began to dam up the product and also began to dump gravel and lime mixture to soak up the product.  The driver notified dispatch and home office of spill.  Home office immediately notified KY EPA, NRC and Weavertown Environmental for remediation and clean-up.
column169: Follow up training was done with the driver.  Safety personnel discussed and made the decision to purchase new caps with locking mechanisms on them which will help eliminate the use of the double-eye hooks. It is Lewis' procedure to also use velcro straps around the dog ears as an additional safety step to secure the cap, however, the strap was not used in this incident.

column168: At 11:30 PM Smith Systems Dispatch was notified by a driver of a substance leaking from his trailer at a Flying J in Anthony, TX.  The driver placed a barrier around the spill for containment and safety.  Environmental Management Inc. (EMI) was contracted for cleanup.    The load consisted of only one hazardous waste manifest #006847034 JJK, it was a load of acids.  EMI contracted D & H Petroleum and Environmental for response to the small release.    D & H determined that the material had an acidic pH.  Upon opening the rear of the trailer they saw one drum with the lid partially open.  D & H speculated that the drum had pressurized causing the container to fail.  Further inspections found one drum lying on its side on the floor, with two additional drums next to it bulging.  D&H staff requested approval to mobilize a skytrack to the site to assist in the offloading of the drums so the floor of the container and the bottom of the pallets could be cleaned.  It is believed that 10-15 gallons was realeased to the trailer floor and 3-4 gallons had ran out of the back of the trailer onto the asphalt.  A notification of the spill was sent to NRC and TCEQ by EMI.  The asphalt was cleaned and power washed under the direction of TCEQ. The one 55-gallon poly drum with the failed lid closure was overpacked and two other closed top poly drums were vented since they were overpressured and were in danger of falling over due to their bottoms being bulged out.  The asphalt was power washed a total of three times until the pH of the rinsate became neutral.  All of the pads utilized to wipe down the two drums that were impacted, the floor, and the bottom of the pallets, were placed into four 55-gallon drums and one 14-gallon drum.  Plastic sheeting was placed beneath the drums/pallets as they were set on the asphalt parking lot during the cleaning process.  The plastic was placed into the five drums after all of the pallets had been reloaded.  All of the liquid captured from power washing the asphalt was placed into the same five drums.  All five containers were placed back onto the truck with all of the other drums and the manifest was adjusted to reflect the additional containers.
column169: The 55-gallon drum that failed was only DOT rated for solids.  The drum was full of liquids.  It is possible that a vented bung is required to transport this material to keep the drums from being overpressurized during transport.

PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OFI RETRAINING IN WORKMETHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGESTATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOPI USE PLENTYOF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. column168: TEAM WAS COMING THROUGH FLAGSTAFF,AZ HEADED TO VALENCIA,CA HIGHWAY PATROL PULLED THEM OVER DUE TO SPARKS/SMOKE COMING FROM REAR OF TANK 51-0390 AN INSULATED  312.  DRIVERS WERE PULLED OVER ON A SIDE ROAD AND SHUT DOWN. TEAM CALLED ME AT   APPROX 23:49 TOLD ME WHAT HAD HAPPENED. ONCE TEAM WAS STOPPED AND TANK WAS IN  SPECTED, THERE WAS NO PRODUCT FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TANK THAT COULD BE SEEN  OR SMELLED.  THERE WERE NO NITRIC ACID CLOUDS OR RUMES FROM THIS PRODUCT.                                                                                  DRIVERS CHECKED THEN INTERNAL/EXTERNAL VALVES, DOME LID, CLEAN OUT CAPS, AND   CHRTISMAS TREE ALL HAD NO SIGNS OF LEAKS. SEEMS THAT NITRIC HAS LEAKED FROM THE  TANK AT SOME POINT AND GOT IN THE INSULATION CAUSING THE SMOKE AND SPARKS. THEN AZ DOT MOVED THEM TO AN ABANDONED REST AREA WHERE A RELIEF TRAILER OFF-LOADED PRODUCT AND CONTINUED WITH DELIVERY WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEM.  ORIGINAL TANK USED FOR THIS SHIPMENT HAS TURNED UP NO INTERNAL CAUSE FOR LEAK.  TRAILER WILL BE BROKEN DOWN TO FIND CAUSE OF LEAK BEFORE PUTTING BACK INTO SERVICE.

column169: APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE WAS ISSED.  BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS! RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OF TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ESPECIALLY THE LONG BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING THE VARIOUS PACKAGES. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING.  ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! WHILE THERE IS POTENTIAL THE BATTERIES MAY HAVE SPARKED TO CAUSE THE FIRE, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INDICATED THEIR INVESTIGATION IS INCONCLUSIVE AND THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE IS UNDETERMINED. column14: US ARMY GARRISON FORT POLK, LA
column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE, SPECIAL FORM NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: THIS INCIDENT DID NOT INVOLVE A SPILL, RELEASE OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL OR PACKAGE FAILURE.  THE NRC OPERATIONS CENTER WAS NOTIFIED VIA PHONE CONVERSATION ON 12 MAY 2010 AT 1650 HOURS AND THEY MADE A LOG BOOK ENTRY OF THE EVENT.  NRC REGION III PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED ON 13 MAY AT 1207 HOURS, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH TAMMY BLOOMER (BRANCH CHIEF OF THE MATERIALS INSPECTION BRANCH (AND DAARRYLE WELDERMANN (HEALTH PHYSICIST).  ON 6 MAY 2010, THE TWO TESTERS WERE SENT VIA FEDEX BY GROUND TRANSPORTATION.  THE TESTERS WERE RETURNED BY FEDEX ON 6 MAY.  FEDEX INDICATED THAT THR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DECLARATION WAS INCOMPLETE.  IT WAS INDICATED THAT REQUIRED INFORMATION SUCH AS NAME OR SYMBOL OF RADIONUCLIDE AND ITS ACTIVITY WERE MISSING; THE TRANSPORT INDEX (TI) WAS NOT TO ONE DECIMAL PLACE AND THAT THR DIMENSIONS OF THE PACKAGE WERE NOT STATED ON THE FORM. ALSO, FEDEX INDICATED THAT THE TYPE A PACKAGE DIDN'T HAVE A TRANSPORTATION SECURITY SEAL AND THAT THE WEIGHT WASN'T MEASURED IN KILOGRAMS.  THE HAZMAT CERTIFIER THEN CORRECTED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DECLARATION AND RE-FFERED THE TESTERS FOR SHIPMENT VIA FEDEX ON 7 MAY 2010.  THE TESTERS WERE AGAIN RETURNED ON 8 MAY 2010.  FEDEX INDICATED THE DEFICIENCIES IN THE DECLARATION WERE: THE YELLOW II AND TI INFORMATION (THE TI WAS A REPEAT DEFICIENCY) WAS MISSING ON THE DECLARATION.  FEDEX ALSO INDICATED IN THEIR REPORT THAT PACKAGE INSTRUCTION COLUMNS MUST BE FILLED WITH CORRECT INFORMATION, THAT THE DECLARATION IS INCOMPLETE AND TH PLEASE REFER TO DG'S SHIPPER AREA AT FEDEX.COM.  THESE DEFICIENCIES ON THE DECLARATION WERE DETERMINED TO BE IN VIOLATION OF 49 CFE 171.16(A)(4) FOR BOTH SHIPMENT DATES.  ALSO THE SHIPPING PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED AS REQUIRED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (DOT) SPECIAL PERMIT (DOT-SP 14568).  THE HAZMAT CERTIFIER (SHIPPING REP) WAS PROVIDED THE DOT SPECIAL PERMIT, IAEA USA CERTIFICATE AND PROCEDURES TO COMPLETE THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS IN MARCH, BUT DID NOT REFER TO THRM PRIOR TO THE TWO ATTEMPTS TO SHIP.  THE HAZMAT CERTIFIER IS A GRADUATE OF THE FOLLOWING COURSES:  RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS HANDLING SAFETY COURSE, US ARMY TACOM AND THE TECHNICAL TRANSPORATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COURSE, US ARMY, DEFENSE AMMUNITION CENTER.
column169: THE HAZMAT CERTIFIER (SHIPPING REPRESENTATIVE) WILL BE TRAINED IN THE PROPER ADMINISTRATIVE RESPONSIBILTIES REQUIRED IN COOMPLETION OF DOCUMENTS FOR SPECIAL PERMIT/YELLOW II ITEMS.  FUTURE SHIPMENTS WILL BE MORE CLOSELY COORDINATED WITH THE INSTALLATION RADIATION SAFELY OFFICER FOR FINAL PREPARATION OF SHIPPING DOCUMENT AND PACKAGING.  ADDITIONALLY, RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL HANDLING PROCEDURES IMPLEMENTED WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF THE INSTALLTION TRANSPORTATION OFFICER AND THE CONTRACTING OFFICER'S REPRESENTATIVE (COR).  FURTHER, A REVIEW OF THE CONTRACT REQUIREMENTS AND SOP/LOCAL REGULATIONS TO ENSURE COORDINATION WITH THE INSTALLATION RSO FOR RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS SHIPMENTS TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE BEYOND THIS INCIDENT.  AVAILABLE TRAINING WILL BE IDENTIFIED TO PROVIDE THE SHIPPING REPRESENTATIVE WITH ADDITIONAL SKILLS REQUIRED TO THOROUGHLY PERFORM THE DUTIES REQUIRED FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPING.  THE SHIPPING DEPARTMENT WILL BE DIRECTED TO CONSTRUCT/ASSEMBLE A BINDER WITH SAMPLE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS BASED ON THE CURRENT REGULATIONS TO BE USED AS A GUIDE FOR THE SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  ALSO, THE SHIPPING REPRESENTATIVE WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO ASK FOR ASSISTANCE WHEN SITUATIONS OCCUR THAT ARE NOT FAMILIAR.

column169: A ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS WAS PERFORMED ON THE INCIDENT IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE.  DURING THE INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CONTRACT DRIVER WAS UNFAMILIAR WITH THE ROADS AND WAS FATIGUED AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE ROAD SIGN INDICATING AN INTERSECTION AHEAD WAS LOCATED OVER A HILL AND NOT FAR ENOUGH AWAY FROM THE INTERSECTION TO ALLOW FOR A TRACTOR TRIALER DRIVER TO SEE THE SIGN AND HAVE ENOUGH DISTANCE TO STOP.

column168: I RECEIVED A CALL ON FRIDAY, MAY 28, 2010 AT APPROX. 10:30AM FROM LA DRIVER RAFAEL SIERRAS.  RAFAEL STATED THAT HE WAS HEADED EAST ON THE 91 FREEWAY EN ROUTE TO KROGER RIVERSIDE TO DELIVER A LOAD OF GAS, 8800 GALLONS. HE CLAIMS THAT THERE WAS AN ACCIDENT INVOLVING A CAR AND A COMMERICAL TRUCK NEXT TO HIM AND THE COMMERCIAL TRUCK WAS PUSHED INTO HIM AND FORCED HIM OFF THE FREEWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER.  NO INJURIES TO REPORT.  RAFAEL STATE THAT HE EXITED THE VEHICLE AND WAS LOOKING AROUND THE TRAILER AND HE SAW A LEAK COMING FROM THE TRAILER AND HE STARTED TO RUN AND A FEW SECONDS LATER, THE TANK EXPLODED AND CAUGHT ON FIRE.  HE CALLED 911 TO REPORT THEN CALL NTL.  I THEN CONTACTED HENRY MEDINA AND INFORMED HIM OF WHAT HAD HAPPENED. HE INSTRUCTED ME TO CALL FEDERATED INSURANCE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  I CALLED FEDERATED AT APPRO. 10:45AM AND SPOKE TO A REPRESENTATIVE AND REPORTED THE ACCIDENT, OUR LOSS# IS: 124592.  AFTER I SPOKE TO FEDERATED, THEY TRANSFERRED ME TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL DEPT THERE AT FEDERATED AND I SPOKE TO TIM AND EXPLAINED THE SITUATION TO HIM AS WELL.  I THEN RECEIVED A CALL FROM JANET AT THE CORONA FIRE DEPT. AND SHE ASKED IF I KNEN THAT ONE OF MY TRUCKS WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT/EXPLOSION AND I SAID YES.  SHE ASKED IF I HAD A COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE ON SITE OR EN ROUTE, I SAID NO BUT I AM WORKING ON IT RIGHT NOW.  I THEN CALLED JUAN MARTINEZ AND TOLD HIM TO HEAD TO THE SCENE.  I THEN CALLED JANET BACK AT THE CORONA FIRE DEPT. AND INSTRUCTED HERE THAT JUAN WAS IN ROUTE AND I GAVE JANET HIS TELEPHONE NUMBER.  AT 11:35AM I RECEIVED A CALL FROM IPS ASKING IF I HAD HEARD ABOUT THE ACCIDENT, I SAID YES, IT WAS US, THEY SAID THEY WERE SORRY AND IF THERE WAS ANYTHING THEY COULD TO DO PLEASE CALL THEM.  I THEN RECEIVED A CALL AT 11:55AM FROM CHEVRON MONTABELLO TERMINAL MANAGER, THEY EXPRESSED THEIR APOLOGIES AND SAID IF WE NEED ANYTHING TO PLEASE LET THEM KNOW.  AT NOON I SPOKE AGAIN TO JANET WHO GAVE ME DIRECTIONS FOR JUAN SINCE THE 91 WAS GOING TO BE SHUT DOWN.  AT 12:03, JUAN IS EN ROUTE TO THE SCENE NOW AND I AM AWAITING FURTHER INSTRUCTION.  AT 12:20PM I RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE CHP ASKING FOR OUR INSURANCE INFORMATION AND OUR DOT NUMBER, I GAVE IT TO THEM.  AT 12:35PM I RECEIVED A CALL FROM BILL KERR WITH CAL TRANS HAZ MAT ASKING IF WE HAD A CLEAN-UP CREW IN ROUTE AND I SAID I AM CALLING THEM NOW.  CALLED PERS AT 12:39PM AND THEY SUPPLIED ME WITH CLEAN-UP CREW NUMBERS AND SOME OFTHER INFO. AT 12:45PM I CALLED PATROIT ENVIRONMENTAL AND THEY HAVE TAKEN THE CASE AND HAVE A REPRESENTATIVE IN ROUTE TO THE SCENE AND WILL BE THERE BY 1:10PM AND THE CREW WILL BE THERE SHORTLY AFTER. SPOKE TO JUAN AT 12:55PM HE IS ON SITE WITH THE CHP AND THE CHP SAYS THEY CANNOT LOCATE RAFAEL ANYWHERE.  MYSELF AND JUAN HAVE TRIED TO CALL RAFAEL A DOZEN TEIMS BUT HE HAS NOT ANSWERED.  AT 1:15PM, TOM WITH FEDERATED CALL AND SAID THAT HE WAS ASSIGNING TETRA TECH TO OUR CASE TO BE ON SITE TO HELP WITH THE WHOLE INCIDENT, FROM ON-SITE SUPERVISION TO THE CLEAN-UP

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS PULLED FOR AN INSPECTION AT THE WB DEARBORN WEIGH STATION.  WHILE THE INSPECTION WAS IN PROCESS A FAINT HISSING SOUND WAS HEARD NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE UNIT WAS ISOLATED AND RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE CONTACTED.  THE GREATER CINCINNATI HAZMAT UNIT WAS 1ST ON THE SCENE.  THE DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE GEAR AND ENTERED THE TRAILER.  A SINGLE CYLINDER OR PROPANE GAS WAS FOUND TO BE SLOWLY LEAKING FROM THE VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAKING WAS SUSPENDED.  THE CYLINDER WAS SECURED, THE AREA IN THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED OF ANY RESIDUE AND THE HAZMAT SUITS RETAINED BY CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL FOR DESTRUCTION.
column169: OUR DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO BE MORE AWARE OF PACKAGE INTEGRITY AND LOADING OPTIONS PRIOR TO RECEIVING HAZMAT LOADS FOR TRANSPORTING, TO THE BEST THAT IS ALLOWED BY THE SHIPPERS.  HE WAS FURTHER INSTRUCTED THAT ALL HAZMAT LOADS MUST BE SECURED AS TO ELIMINATE AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE BOTH FORWARD AND BACKWARD MOVEMENT AS WELL AS SIDE TO SIDE MOVEMENT OF ALL SHIPPED PACKAGES.  DRIVER WAS FURTHER INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ONCE IN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT EMERGENCY PERSONNEL SHOULD BE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND STEPS TAKEN TO SECURE THE AREA AND ANY PEOPLE IN THE AREA WERE INSTITUTED (AS DID OCCUR IN THIS MATTER).
