column168: MIKE HARRISON AND I WERE ABOUT TO LEAVE DALE WIEDENFELD'S OFFICE, WHEN I LOOKED UP TO THE LOADING RACK AREA, I THEN SAW A FLASH FIRE IGNITE AT BAY FOUR, WHERE AN ANDREWS TRANSPORTATION TANKER TRAILER WAS LOADING.  THE FLASH CAME OUT, AND UP FROM UNDER THE TANKER AS IS MADE AN EXPLOSIVE THUD.  I INFORMED THE TWO OF THE FIRE, AND RAN TO THE LOADING RACK AREA, APPROACHING IT FROM THE JPTS TANK FARM AREA.  I COULD SEE A LARGE NUMBER OF THE MATNTENANCE PERSONNEL ENGAGING THE FIRE FROM THE SOUTH END OF THE RACK, UTILIZING FIRE MONITORS, STEAM SNUFFING SYSTEM, AND THE OVERHEAD SPRINKLER WAS ON. I THEN RAN INTO THE LOADING RACK OFFICE TO ENGAGE THE E-STOP BUTTON AND ELECTRONICALLY SHUT OFF ALL PUMPS THAT MAY BE ON.  I THEN ENGAGED THE FIRE WITH THE FIRE MONITOR ON THE NORTH WEST SIDE OF THE LOADING RACK, BUT I WAS TOO FAR TO REACH THE BASE OF THE FIRE ON BAY FOUR.  I DECIDED TO MOVE TO THE FIRE MONITOR ON THE NORTH EAST SIDE OF THE LOADING RACK, JUST NORTH OF THE TANKER ON FIRE.  THIS MONITOR HAD A FOAM DRUM ATTACHED TO IT, SO I ENGAGED IT AND SPRAYED FOAM FROM THERE, I COULD SEE THAT PHIL GOODMAN ATTACKING FROM THE OPPOSITE MONITOR ON THE SOUTH EAST MONITOR.  THIS APPEARED TO NOT HAVE AN EFFECT ON THE FIRE AS IT CONTINUED TO GROW AND HEAT UP.  I THEN HEARD AN EXPLOSION AND HEAT FLARE UP, I THEN FELT I WAS TOO CLOSE TO THE ENGULFED TANKER AND FEARED FOR MY SAFETY, SO I LOCKED THE FOAM MONITOR INTO THE POSITION I HAD IT, AND RAN BACK TO THE SOUTH WEST MONITOR.  I COULD SEE FLAMES START TO COME UP THROUGH THE GRADING THROUGHOUT THE RACK AND BEHIND THE LOADING RACK OFFICE;I THEN FOUGHT THOSE FLAMES WITH THAT MONITOR.  WE ALL CONTINUED TO FIGHT THIS FIRE UNTIL I HEARD AJ VOLGER GIVE THE ORDER TO ABANDON THE FIGHT, AND TO LET THE BETTER EQUIPPED SAFD TAKE OVER.  WE WERE THEN GIVEN ORDERS, BY COMPANY RADIO TO CLOSE ALL PRODUCT TANKS THAT FED THE LOADING RACK, BY PHIL GOODMAN.  I ASSISTED THOMAS LOCKHART, AND TRAVIS CRUMP, IN CLOSING AS MANY SALES AND MAKE VALVES AS POSSIBLE.  AFTER THIS WE RETREATED FROM THE PLANT AND MET FOR ACCOUNTABILITY SOUTH OF THE PLANT.  LATER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT WE MIGHT HAVE OVER LOOKED CLOSING TANKS 434 AND 425, SO IT WAS DECIDED THAT I GO IN WITH A TEAM FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, TO SHOW THEM, FROM A SAFE DISTANCE, WHICH VALVES TO CLOSE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CLOSED BOTH 434 AND 425.  AFTER THIS WE RETREATED BACK TO THE SAFE ZONE AND AWAITED RTFC, TO COME IN AND FINISH EXTINGUISHING REMAINING FLAMES.  AT APPROXIMATELY 11:20AM THE FIRE STARTED IN THE EAST BAY AT THE TRUCK RACK WERE IT SPREAD THROUGH THE REMAINDER OF THE TRUCK RACK.  THE FIRE WAS CONCLUDED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00PM.  THERE WERE FOUR TRUCKS INVOLVED.  THE TRUCKS FROM EAST TO WEST WERE ANDREWS, ANDREWS, JUNG OIL, AND STEVE GOREA (OWNER/OPERATOR) WITH A UPT TRAILER.  THE FIRST ANDREWS' TRUCK WAS LOADING REFORMATE (ESTIMATED 8000 GAL).  THE SECOND ANDREWS' TRUCK WAS WAITING TO LOAD (EMPTY).  THE JUNG OIL TRUCK HAD COMPLETED LOADING DIESEL (ESTIMATED 7500 GAL).  THE UPT TRU
column169: CA NUMBER 1:  RELOCATE THE LOADING RACK OPERATORS OFFICE TO A POSITION AWAY FROM THE LOADING RACK AND INTO A POSITION WHICH WILL PROVIDE A BETTER VIEW OF THE LOADING OPERATION.  ALSO, INVESTIGATE THE NEED TO INSTALL A PRESSURE RESISTANT BUILDING.  CA NUMBER 2:  REVIEW THE USE OF A NEW GROUNDING SYSTEM (REBUILT LOADING RACK) THAT WILL NOT BE BYPASSED BY TRUCK DRIVERS.  CA NUMBER 3:  REVIEW CURRENT FIRE SUPPRESSION SYSTEM TO EVALUATE ADDITIONAL ALTERNATIVES, INCLUDING BUT NO LIMITED TO MORE FOAM, THE OILY WATER PIT AREA, AND A MUTUAL AID AGREEMENT WITH RANDOLPH AIR FORCE BASE'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  CA NUMBER 4:  REVIEW PROCEDURES TO AUDIT THRID PARTY CARRIERS WHO LOAD AND UNLOAD AT AGE REFINERY'S TRUCK RACKS.  CA NUMBER 5:  HOLD A PSM COMMITTEE MEETING TO DETERMINE OTHER CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO BE CONSIDERED.

ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO STORAGE DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: AS THE VEHICLE WAS PROPERLY MAINTAINED AND INSPECTED, OUR COMPANY CANNOT IMPROVE ON THE PARTICULAR AREA OF CONCERN ON THIS VEHICLE WHICH CAUSED THIS RELEEASE.  WE HAVE CONTACTED OUR BULK STORAGE TANK INSTALLATION COMPANY AND HAVE INFORMED THEM OF THE CAUSE FOR THIS INCIDENT AND THEY ASSURE US THEY WILL BE AWARE OF THIS TYPE OF PROBLEM IN THE FUTURE.  ALL OTHER VEHICLES HAVE BEEN INSPECTED TO ASSURE AS BEST AS POSSIBLE THAT THE SAME FAULT WILL NOT OCCUR AGAIN.

column168: Driver spotted his loaded gasoline tanker at the station to begin unloading. Driver had stuck the tanks for inventory readings. After sticking tanks, driver hooked delivery drop hoses to correct tanks. When driver opened discharge valve for straight NL compartment, coming off trailer to tank the delivery hose began leaking at hose coupling to tight fill connection. Before driver could close valve, approximately 25 gallons of gasoline was released onto parking lot. Less than 5 gallons of the released gasoline got into an open sewer drain. Local fire department was called out and they flushed the sewer free of any flammable product. Fire department tested the sewer and cleared it.
column169: All drivers have been notified that they need to double check their hose connections prior to opening any product valves. This was not a equipment problem but a human error problem.

column168: Release Description and Location:  On May 18, 2010 at approximately 12:30 pm, an Airgas box style truck was in route between the Dedham Wastewater Treatment Plant(WWTP) in Dedham, MA and Boston College in Brighton, MA to deliver chlorine gas cylinders and pick up empty cylinders. After the driver stopped to deliver the cylinders to Boston College, the driver noticed an odor, presumably chlorine, emanating from the back of the vehicle in the vicinity of 2635 Beacon Street in Brighton, MA. The incident response and sealing of the leak occurred at this location.  The area where the incident response occurred consists of a two lane roadway with curb side parking and is surrounded by residences and classroom buildings of Boston College.
column169: Steps taken to Prevent Recurrence of Future Leaks:  Airgas has taken the following steps to address root and contributing causes of the incident so as to prevent a future recurrence of this type of event:  1) Discussed with Alexander Chemical the need to change their shipping protocol with respect to lead gaskets.  2) Will conduct training sessions with Dedham (WWTP) personnel on properly preparing "empty" cylinders for shipment back to supplier.  3) Raised awareness of the event within Airgas by conducting a safety meeting with associates where the root and contributing causes of the release were discussed as well as preventive measures we are taking to prevent such an occurrence in the future.

column168: On Friday, May 21,2010, Our driver left the Delek terminal in Tyler, Texas on route to Whitehouse, Texas. He was loaded with 8500 gallons of gasoline. He traveled on Loop 323 to Hwy 110 South. As he approached the intersection, he observed traffic in both left turn lanes. He took the inside lane due to fewer vehicles. While at the red light, he saw another truck in the outside turn lane approximately three quarters of the way back of his trailer. When the light turned green, he proceeded to make his turn. He was still in low gear and could not have been going more than 15-20 MPH as he felt his tractor-trailer turning over. He got out of the truck and noticed there was damage to the other truck making the turn at the same time he was. The driver of the other truck approached our driver and neither was sure what caused our truck to turn over.   When the trailer hit the pavement, the #1 compartment (2600 gal. capacity) ruptured in a small area. Approximately 300 gallons of gasoline with 10% ETH was spilled from the compartment   The EMS, city police and fire department were on the scene immediately. The area was immediately evacuated and the fire department laid down Spagsorb and foam to contain the spill. The fuel that did spill was contained by a dam that was built by the first arriving engine crew. The other truck had a torn fuel tank and a small amount of diesel spilled from it. The tear in the tanker was plugged with a patch applied by TFD Hazmat. After the spill was contained and stopped the hazmat team called for a tanker to off load to and when it arrived the overturned truck was drilled and tapped by the hazmat crew. The gasoline was then offloaded into tanker The holes that were drilled were covered to control any remaining vapors and foam was applied during the entire operation to control vapor A wrecker was then called to upright the truck and trailer.
column169: Even though we feel that our truck was clipped by the truck coming around him on the right side, we have taken steps to prevent any recurrences.   1. Hired a new Safety Director.   2. column168: Note that the accident location is in Weston County, and although emergency responders came from both Crook and Weston Counties, it was Weston County officials who managed the response operations and retained jurisdiction over the incident.   The Maverik fuel transport truck was operated by a Maverik driver together with a driver trainee who was a passenger. Both men were taken to the hospital by ambulance for evaluation after the accident. Earlier in the day they had reportedly loaded the transport with unleaded fuel at the Wyoming Refining Sheridan terminal, where the typical amount loaded is reportedly 10,800 gallons. From the terminal, they apparently drove to Maverik store #165 in Gillette where they unloaded 5,999 gallons into the #3 unleaded tank as recorded by the Veeder-Root console at that store (see Veeder-Root records reproduced below). No other tank at that store showed an increase yesterday afternoon, and no delivery at all was recorded yesterday afternoon at store #282 also in Gillette. So, the transport still had on board 4,800 gallons yesterday when they left Gillette apparently bound for Newcastle. Of this total, 1,000 gallons was held by the trailer which did not overturn in the accident. The tank that was on the main truck chassis would have held the remaining 3,800 gallons. That tank became separated from the truck chassis when it overturned, and apparently all 3,800 gallons of fuel were spilled onto the ground.   After securing the accident scene, the emergency responders from Crook and Weston Counties addressed the fuel spill by using absorbent booms and pads, digging diversion ditches to keep the fuel contained, and placing stoppers in drainage culverts. The Weston County Emergency Manager is Doug Jorrey, and he said that these measures were successful to a large degree but that they were concerned that fuel had reached an adjacent stock-watering pond. Our insurer is Great West Property and Casualty, and they sent an investigator to the site from Rapid City, SD yesterday afternoon for an initial assessment. They also retained the services of an environmental consultant who will be coordinating additional response actions. Great West is taking an active environmental management and oversight role and so no additional effort on our part is needed.
column169: MAVERIK SENT DRIVER TRAINER TO HELP TRAIN AND SUPPORT JERRY HAMMOND.

column168: According to the available information, Jemigan Oil Company, Inc. (Jernigan) mistakenly delivered diesel fuel to this facility on May 17, 2010. During the off-loading of fuel, the 10,000-gallon diesel fuel above ground storage tank (AST) reached capacity and the top of the AST ruptured releasing approximately 100 gallons of fuel. immediately after the AST ruptured, the pump on the transport tanker was stopped. Jernigan personnel were immediately mobilized to the facility to begin abatement activities. Absorbent booms/pads were utilized to recover ponding product. Geological Resources, Inc. (GRI) was notified by Jemigan personnel in the evening of May 17, 2010. GRI staff was mobilized to the site on May 18, 2010 to direct and supervise the initial abatement activities. The National Response Center and the North Carolina Department of Environment and Natural Resources (NCDENR) were notified on May 18, 2010. The National Response Center issued Incident Number 940688 for the release. The NCDENR issued Incident Number 93078 for the release.   Initial abatement activities were conducted. in May and June 2010. Approximately 100.28 tons of contaminated soil were transported to permitted disposal facility. Confirmation soil samples were collected at the conclusion of excavation activities. No soil quality violations were measured in the confirmation soil samples. The NCDENR issued a No Further Action determination on August 18, 2010.

column168: A TANKER TRUCK ACCIDENT SUNDAY IN SOUTH SUTTER COUNTY SPILLED A CARGO TOXIC AMMONIA, BLOCKING A SECTION OF HIGHWAY 99 FOR MORE THAN SEVEN HOURS. THE DOUBLE TRACTOR-TRAILER FLIPPED ONTO ITS SIDE AT ABOUT 3:05 P.M. AS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO TURN LEFT FROM SOUTHBOUND HIGHWAY 99 ONTO NICOLAUS AVENUE, ACCORDING TO THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL. THE FRONT TANK OF TWO RUPTURED, RELEASING AQUEOUS AMMONIA SOLUTION ONTO THE ROAD SHOULDER, CAPT. JIM YOUNG OF THE YUBA CITY CHP OFFICE SAID. THE DRIVE, RICHARD DEAN SPENCE, 62, OF WHEATLAND, WAS NOT INJURED IN THE ACCIDENT. OFFICERS CLOSED HIGHWAY 99 IN BOTH DIRECTIONS AS A HAZMAT CREW WORKED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE HIGHWAY, THE MAIN LINK BETWEEN YUBA CITY AND SACRAMENTO, REOPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:25 P.M., ACCORDING TO THE CHP WEBSITE. SOUTHBOUND TRAFFIC WAS DIVERTED FROM 99 TO HIGHWAY 113, WHERE DRIVERS COULD TAKE GEORGE WASHINGTON BOULEVARD NOTRH TO YUBA CITY OR CONTINUE ON 113 TO YOLO COUNTY. NORTHBOUND MOTORISTS ON 99 WERE DETOURED TO HIGHWAY 70 TOWARDS MARYSVILLE. A ROADBLOCK SEALED OFF LOCAL TRAFFIC ON THE HIGHWAY AT SACRAMENTO AVENUE NORTH OF THE SPILL. SPENCE WAS HAULING AN AMMONIA SHIPMENT TO THE PLEASANT GROVE AREA WHEN HE TOOK A TURN TOO QUICKLY OFF THE HIGHWAY, YOUNG SAID SUNDAY NIGHT.  AQUEOUS AMMONIA CONSISTS OF 20 PERCENT AMMONIA GAS DISSOLVED IN WATER AND IS USED AS A AGRICULTURAL FERTILIZER. THE CHP SEALED OFF A LARGE ARE AROUND THE WRECK BECAUSE OF FEARS A NORTHWESTERLY WIND COULD CAUSE THE GAS TO BECOME AIRBORNE AND SICKEN PEOPLE IN OTHER AREAS. OFFICERS TOLD AT LEAST TWO HOMEOWNERS SOUTH OF THE HIGHWAY 99-NICOLAUS AVENUE INTERCHANGE TO CLOSE THEIR WINDOWS, BUT NO EVACUATIONS WERE ORDERED AND NO INJURIES REPORTED, ACCORDING TO THE CHP.  CALTRANS OFFICIALS WERE AT THE CRASH SCENE TO SUPERVISE THE CLEANUP, WHICH INVOLVES REMOVING SOIL CONTAMINATED BY THE LIQUID. WHEN THE TANKER WENT OVER THE IMPACT MADE A HOLE, WHICH RESULTED IN THE SPILLAGE.

column168: On Tuesday, May 11, 2010, at approximately 1840, the security guard received a call from a motorist, stating that there was product spilling in the roadway. The security guard called the Shipping supervisor who proceeded to the highway and had the phosphoric acid tankerman shutdown the barge unloading pump at approximately 6:45, upon discovery of the add spill on the highway. 30% phosphoric acid solution was being transferred from the barge to the Mosaic Fertilizer - Faustina Facility. The acid spilled onto the roadway (Hwy 18) and the area between the west side of the highway and the plant’s fence line. There was no sign of acid on the east side of the highway or on the levee. The cause of the spill was due to a failure on a stainless steel phosphoric acid transfer line.
column169: (1) The entire run of phosphoric acid unloading line under went ultrasonic inspection for thickness.   (2) The section of stainless steel piping was replaced with upgraded specifications.   (3) Recommendation to encase piping running above public highway in a conduit to contain leaks/spills and recover encased piping contents within the facility.

column168: Customer (Bane Cheek), arrived at our MCO Airport for a flight to LAS.  Before boarding, our Employee asked the Customer what type of batteries were installed in the wheelchair. The Customer stated "I just had the wheelchair serviced and they installed Non-Spillable batteries in the wheelchair".  Because there is an exception in the regulation to allow non-spillable batteries to remain installed, our ramp agent loaded the wheelchair in the cargo bin for transport.  Upon landing in HOD, our Ramp Agent opened the bin and noticed the batteries had spilled. The wheelchair was removed and after further investigation, it was noted that the company who serviced the wheelchair for Mr. Cheek had actually installed spillable batteries instead of the non-spillable ones that he had requested.  The wheelchair was cleaned and the batteries were removed and packaged properly per 49 CFR 175.10.  The wheelchair and batteries were then allowed to be transported with the Customer to their final destination of LAS.  The aircraft was taken our of service and thoroughly cleaned.
